caption: A variety of food places to choose from in downtown Brooklyn, centrally located with Trader Joe’s and Target not too far away. This Crepe place sells the sweet and savory, breakfast style or as a light entree. It is made to the order and just delicious!

This was my 1st time visiting the store and I enjoyed my strawberry banana crepe very much.  It was soft, tasty and very fulfilling.  I can’t wait to go back and try others.  My only reason for rating 4 stars is because they are in grub hub and I don’t love far but some how, they don’t deliver to me.  Oh well
Great crepe counter with lovely stuff. Thoughtfully put together recipes and gluten free rice flour for all crepes. Highly recommend for a quick bite.
Good place very good food and amaizing stuff . Tom is the best thank you
Delicious and good service is top notch you have to try this place out I had the blt
Poor customer service.
Delicious
This place made my wife’s day! Gluten-free and worth every penny. We went back for the #12 the next day!
Amazing 🤤
Located downstairs in the Dekalb Market Hall.
Wow. I love crepes. I’ve had them all around the world and the Nutella crepe I had here! One of the best. Not the best but pretty darn good. It’s in the basement of the mall in the Dekalb Market.
I ordered their gammon ham, cheese & egg crepes. Crepe is soft, filling & delicious!
Very delicious especially for gluten free!!!
So Delicious!! The fruits used are fresh and the crepes is so tasty 😍😍
I got a strawberry Nutella crepe Barely any strawberries It was good but it only came with 3 If you’re lucky it’s 4

Delicious, soft, tasty gluten free crepes! I don’t know why this isn’t a bigger deal but if you’re gluten intolerant and need a sweet fix this is the place to be. You guys would do so great in a brunch environment with these crepes! 💜💜 btw these are filling af, count on it being a whole meal!

While you can get a crepe in many places, you have not lived until you've had a crepe cone from Eight Turn Crepe. They offer you the ability to customize your own crepes, allowing for various creme fillings, fruits, nuts, and other sweet and savory toppings. The Chocolate Truffles are a must-include topping, and definitely pay the extra dollar for the S'mores Ice Cream. It is sooooo worth it
I haven't had crêpes in years bc of my gluten allergy and this was amazing
Delicious crepes!
Amazing place
Help I'm addicted! Delicious sweet crepes and they have student discount as well. Highly recommend trying the ramune soda as well
in a matter of a week, i visited three times. definitely worth it

Loved this place since the time is used to be open in SoHo! My preferred Harajuku style crepe place for various reasons. The options are all wonderful (the savory and the sweet are all good choices) and very filling as well. The crepes themselves are crispy on the outside but still soft, which I appreciated. Like I said, very filling, so if you're going to get some sweet crepes for dessert, maybe walk around a bit or take it slow.

One of the cheap handheld crepes I've had in NY and great tasting too. I went during a Saturday afternoon and the place was somewhat crowded. Difficult to find on maps if new to the area as it's inside the Delkab Food court building. They even offer discounts to other food court vendors with your receipt.

Delicious Japanese-style rice crepes made right in front of your eyes. Great service and plenty of savory & sweet options to choose from, whether you want a dessert or something more filling as a meal - the Eight Turn Lox is a crowd fav. The savory crepe I got (eight turn famous BLT with shrimp) could’ve come with more filling. Will come back to try the sweet crepes. Also, flash your student ID for 10% off!
Fast, friendly, informative service with great tasting crepes
Awesome awesome treat. Theyre a little expensive and there isnt good seating in the area, but thats not their fault. the food is excellent and its made pretty quickly.
I love this place hope they never close
I tried the chocolate crepe and it was really good, wasn't a heavy dessert, the crepe it's not greasy. Highly recommended.
Excellent Japanese style rice flour crepes. Strongly reminds me of the ones I had in Harajuku in Tokyo.
nice japanese crepes lots of choices really limited seating ice cream is extra, but very much worth it
Pretty tasty crepes, but I had to wait a while for my order after I paid.
(Translated by Google) Very rich and good service Local small but nice  (Original) Muy Ricossssss y buena atención Local pequeño pero agradable
Love this place! The crepes are so good. They're reasonably priced and are delicious! Would recommend and I'm definitely going back!
The best crêpes in town!

Japanese style crepe which you will need to hold it in your hands like a sundae cone. The crepe itself is made from rice ingredients so it has a very unique taste. They have both sweet and savory crepes, but in my opinion, the sweet one tastes better. The portion is large, and may be too much for dessert after a meal. So I would come eat the crepes here as a snack. The place is kinda small but most likely you take it out and eat it at a near by park. I recommend their matcha crepe.
The place seems a bit dirty, and the costumer service is not that good. But the crepe is really good.
Really good crepe! The actual space inside is tiny and there's a decent wait (10-15 minutes) between ordering and getting your crepe, but it's worth it
(Translated by Google) Super good just not too much place to sit. Reasonable price.  (Original) Super bon juste pas trop de place pour s'asseoir. Prix raisonnable.
Fantastic crepes! Really enjoyed Lychee Valentine
great eat
Awesome service and food! Absolutely loved everything from the start to the end!

Best Japanese style crepes I've had outside of Tokyo! Slightly sweet, crispy, golden crepes filled with delicious cremes and topped with fruit, chocolates or ice cream. Softly rolled up and wrapped in a paper cone. Ah. May. Zing
Awful experience.  The wait time was ridiculous and i didnt even get my food. I just canceled the order.  Also the workers hygienic practices today were questionable..... completely let down.

The decoration inside is a bit questionable with loud (but admittedly fun) graphics inside as if it wanted to scream that the crepe was Japanese. It isn't exactly Japanese style. Though I think it's delicious, the crepe is a bit too dry and not soft enough. The combinations that are the most similar to what are offered in harajuku are too expensive too. I like some american fillings like peanut butter though.
Very good
Really great! Not only is the presentation beautiful, the crepes are that perfect combo of crispy and chewy. Try the Lychee Valentine, with a lemony cream and rose petals.
Amazing! Gluten and celiac friendly full of flavor. Neat little place.
Eight Turn is a little pricey, but their crepes are absolutely marvelous, and remind me of those I enjoyed in Japan. The Peanut Butter and Banana crepe is a real treat!
Great for dessert.
Amazing gluten free crepes. Need I say more?

This place makes craving a late night snack good. I like how you can watch the magic happen right in front of you. The shrimp and avacado crepe was love at first bite. It is a great selection to choose from. The space is small with a few chairs to sit and eat. It is definitely worth it.
So amazing....everyone should check this out. Blavo.

Delicious gluten free Crêpes. I had the BLT and really loved the flavor, it even had a little spice to it. This is a small establishment, not really a good place to try to sit down and eat, but a fun place to stop by for a on the go meal.
very tasty!
Giving it a 4 out of 5. Very good quality, but I don't think the price it has and an additional 2$ avacado, is necessary.
Very, very good!!

Place is small, but in front of the uptown 6 train entrance, very convenient.  They have many unique names for their crepes and creations.  You can make you own topping and filling, but I went with the Harajuku cocktail ( Strawberries, almonds, blueberries, raspberries, and some cream).  The crepe was pretty crispy.  It needed a bit more cream, it was a little on the drier side.  Small seating area infront of the windows and a bench on the wall.  This place is tiny, but I liked their packaging when you take it to go. Almost like eating a burrito, and you peel the wrapper as you go down chopping on the crepe.  They accept all major credit cards, you swipe sign your name on their ipads.  I would prefer them having some hand sanitizer next to their counter because everyone probably touched that ipad with their dirty fingers..then you have to eat your awesome crepe with a fork...I sometimes prefer my fingers for those crucial moments when needed.

Solid japanese crepe place. Sadly they are just a store front, with no tables and chairs but their savory and sweet choice crepes are excellent, with a japanese flair. I had a red bean crepe and it was delicious. I also had their crepe dog with band ketchup and tofu one as well and they were just a lovely eating experience. I will be back, when I'm in the neighborhood, to grab a crepe on the go.
Delish gourmet crepes. The store's a bit tiny, but they've got some yummy crepes so I'll forgive. Bit pricey. Totally recommend the signature BLT crepe.

This is a really cute crepe place in Soho with Japanese style crepes. Although there's barely any room to stay and eat in there the park down the block is a good alternative. I had to Harajuku Fruit Cocktail and loved it! The crepe itself was crisp and the fruits were ripe. The almond slices were w great touch and the custard was sweet.  The yozosoda was also great! Full of citrus and nicely chilled! I wish they would offer it in hot tea form for the upcoming winter weather though.

Eight Turn Crepes is one of the two locations for this fantastic crepe shop. The other is in the adopted homeland of crepes, Tokyo, Japan. Either location you visit is delicious, although the NYC branch uses rice flour instead of regular flour (because Americans think gluten is bad - hint, it's not).  That being said, the crepes are delicious. I enjoyed the kurubota sausage crepe, and nearly walked back in for a sweet crepe right afterwards. Try 8 Turn. You won't be disappointed.
Their strawberry and banana crêpe with yogurt it's the best I give them five stars it's my new guilty pleasure

Take out crepe store with a couple of seats, with fillings way beyond the everyday creperie.  Wakame sesame.  Yes.  Teriyaki chicken.  Yes. Tofu edamame.  Yes.  Truffle egg white omelet.  Well, I'm not really into ordering eggs.  But Truffle oil.  Hell yeah. Both savory and sweet varieties,  with coffee and shakes.  Unless you want the 'regular' varieties of crepes, this is defiantly the place to go.  Best crepe store around.
Nice light crepes, great when you need a sweet fix.

the first crepe I tried was my cup of tea, and it was awesome you guys should get the matcha stripes crepe, I think that's what it's called. :3 later I'll ask my sister to go to that crepe shop again! ^ ^
Creative
Love the tuna nicoise, NY blueberry cheese cake.
ummmm....how I love thee. You taste so good in my belly. You are always fresh and always tasty, every time I eat thee I want more in my tummy.
Quite expensive, but it is pretty filling considering that it's just a crepe with lots of delicious things! The place was packed! Be prepared to bring around $8 at least.
Not a sit-down place.  Few seats for folks who want to sit and enjoy their food.  Good for savory or sweet.  It's more than enough for a meal.

I had the pleasure to try these delicious crepes at the Intel Popup back in January.  The Matcha Stripe Chocolate crepe had ripe strawberries, chocolate sauce, housemade chocolate truffles, whipped yogurt, matcha custard cream and crushed pistachios. It tasted light, without feeling overly sweet.  The finished masterpiece was definitely too pretty to eat; this crepe was $7.  If let's say you were allergic to nuts, they would be more than happy to leave it out for you.  I would definitely go again for the Matcha Stripe Chocolate or to try any of their other sweet or savory crepes, which include a cheesecake crepe as well!
is good
Best crepes in the city, hands down. They have a perfect texture, high quality ingredients, and excellent flavor. This place is better then going to France!

Japanese crepe place with cute display of all options in the window! Highly recommend this place vs. the one just a few stores down.  The lox crepe is amazing! Truffle crepe is very healthy tasting, maybe it's not their better one.  I must try their dessert crepes soon (matcha green tea ice cream, etc), but I always eat their savory crepe and end up being too full for the sweet ones..
Everything here is amazing. I have been here plenty of times and it gets better each time.

We tried the truffle omlette crepe and the tofu edamame crepe-both were delicious, filling, healthy and fresh.  They are served in amazing peel-away paper cones which makes them surprisingly easy to eat on the go

Food (5/5)   Decor (4/5)   Service (3/5)  The crepes here are amazing.  I had the matcha stripe chocolate crepe and the strawberry plus chocolate chunks plus thin wrapper worked together harmoniously.  The wrapping of the crepe is also very innovative.  They fold it up into a cone shape and wrap paper around it so you can hold it and eat it like an ice cream cone almost.  The paper is perforated so that as you eat, you can keep peeling the paper away in a neat and orderly fashion.  The yuzu lemonade, which was being offered as a free promotion when I went, was also really tasty and reminded me of a normal lemonade with an extra citrus burst.  The service here was only so so though.  The person taking our orders was a little brusque and rough around the edges.  Also, they were doing a buy one crepe get one yuzu lemonade free promotion, and when they forgot to give us our lemonades, I asked for mine only to be greeted with a look and tone of suspicion.  Thoroughly off putting.  Also, if you plan on coming with a group for brunch, you might have to take it to the park across the street to eat as the place does not have any place to sit.  I would certainly come back to this place for the crepes as I feel the taste alone has merited that.  Just don't expect to stellar service.

Crepe Cones! The Japanese always come up with the coolest things and food is no different. They’ve managed to take traditional crepes and turned them into cones that one can eat on the go, similar to how one would eat an ice cream cone. It works out wonderfully and the choices are as vast as one would find at any traditional creperie, such as Vive le Crepe. The first outpost is in NoLita, right when you exit the 6 train on Spring Street. It is a little spot with minimal seating by the windows and the majority of the space dedicated to the kitchen. The windows feature full on display cones showing the various types they offer to any passersby, from the sweet to the savory. On the right hand side of that inside the shop are LCD screens depicting the origins of the location, Japanese girls eating crepe cones, as well as delectable visuals of the insides of these cones and their ingredients. The menu is displayed atop, as well as a portable menu on the counter so you can make your pick. The entire place seems to be digitized and you order you sign for your card by finger on a tablet, just like most small businesses in the city are starting to do these days. Now unto the food. They’re really good and they are worth the price. They are comparable to other crepe locations and at times even cheaper. However, they are just as filling and look just as pretty, as evidenced by the pictures in this post. I’ve been there twice already and the strawberry banana is my favorite. They have a plethora of fruit flavors and savory ones that include turkey or ham with lettuce. I haven’t tried them but they look really good. I recommend you stop by as soon as possible as everyone was asking where we got it from when we were eating them on the train, so I expect the place to be swarmed soon.
I had Tofu Edamame. It was so delicious. I loved the crepe itself. My new favorite stop in Soho.
I went the savory route with the chicken teriyaki crepe...two thumbs up. I'm coming back for more.
